---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="MP Men's Training Short Sleeve T-Shirt (Dark Grey) — Myprotein PDP">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: MP Men's Training Short Sleeve T-Shirt</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein Product Detail Page &mdash; Audited 4 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      Audit of the Dark Grey colourway PDP at myprotein.com/p/sports-clothing/mp-men-s-training-short-sleeve-t-shirt-dark-grey/17479465/,
      reviewed at desktop viewport (1440px). The page has a clean two-column layout with a strong hero image gallery,
      but the product panel is critically underpowered: price, colour swatches, and star ratings are all absent from
      the main content area — DOM inspection reveals empty containers where these elements should render, suggesting
      a CMS or API data issue rather than a design decision. Combined with a near-empty product description and
      conflicting delivery messaging, the page creates meaningful friction at the point of evaluation.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Price absent from the product panel"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="price-missing-panel"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The product price (£20.00) does not appear in the main right-hand product panel — it is only visible
        in the sticky bottom bar alongside the Add to Basket button. The panel layout has a large blank gap
        between the product title and the Size Guide row where price would conventionally sit.
        DOM inspection confirms two empty containers (<code>flex flex-col gap-4</code> and <code>flex flex-col gap-3</code>)
        in this position, consistent with content that failed to render.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-mp-training-tshirt-dark-grey-2026-06-04/above-fold-desktop.png" alt="Above-fold view showing large blank gap in product panel between title and size selector, with price only in the sticky bar" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Price is one of the most critical signals a user needs before committing to add a product to their basket.
        Hiding it below the fold in the sticky bar means users evaluating the product cannot see what they'll pay
        without scrolling past all options. This breaks the standard mental model for PDP layouts and is likely to
        increase hesitation and reduce add-to-basket rate.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Investigate why the price component is not rendering in the panel content area. The empty container divs
        suggest a data-binding failure — check that the product pricing data is correctly passed to the panel
        template and that the price component mounts successfully. Price should appear directly below the product
        title, above the size selector, consistent with standard ecommerce PDP patterns.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Colour swatches missing from product panel"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="colour-swatches-missing"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        No colour variant swatches are visible in the product panel. The DOM contains a colour-selector element
        and a "Black" colour button, confirming at least one other colourway exists, but these are not rendering
        in the panel. The breadcrumb correctly shows "Dark Grey" as the current variant but there is no visual
        indicator in the panel, and no way for users to discover or switch to other colour options.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-mp-training-tshirt-dark-grey-2026-06-04/product-panel-desktop.png" alt="Product panel with no colour swatches visible anywhere between title and size selector" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Colour selection is a primary decision point for clothing. If a user lands on a colourway that is out of
        stock or not their preference, they have no visible path to alternatives — increasing the chance of
        abandonment rather than a variant switch. This also suppresses cross-sell between colourways.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Same root cause as the missing price — the colour selector component is failing to mount in the panel.
        Ensure the variant data (all available colours and their stock status) is correctly passed to the panel
        template. Colour swatches should render directly beneath the price, using circular or rounded-square
        swatches with the selected colour clearly indicated.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="No product star rating or review count on the PDP"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="reviews-missing"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        There are no star ratings or review counts anywhere on the product page. The site-level trust bar in the
        header references "Over 210k reviews &amp; 4.4 rated" globally, but no per-product rating is shown.
        This is particularly noticeable given the large blank gap in the panel where reviews are typically displayed.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Star ratings are among the highest-impact trust signals on a PDP and directly influence add-to-basket
        conversion. Their absence — particularly on a basic training garment where users may be price-comparing
        with competitors — leaves a gap that social proof would fill. If the product has reviews, not showing
        them is leaving conversion on the table.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        If this product has reviews, surface a star rating and review count directly below the product title (or
        below the colour swatches). Link it to a review section lower on the page. If the review widget is failing
        to load, investigate the data source. If the product genuinely has no reviews, consider a "Be the first to
        review" prompt rather than silence.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Product description contains only 'Range: Clothing'"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={false}
      findingId="thin-product-description"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The "Product Details" accordion expands to reveal only a single line: <strong>Range: Clothing</strong>.
        There is no fabric content, fit description, care instructions, or feature callouts. The accordion itself
        requires a click to reveal even this minimal content.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-mp-training-tshirt-dark-grey-2026-06-04/product-details-accordion-desktop.png" alt="Product Details accordion open showing only 'Range: Clothing'" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        For a training t-shirt, fabric composition (e.g. polyester percentage, moisture-wicking properties) and
        fit type (regular, slim, relaxed) are active purchase decision criteria. Their absence creates uncertainty
        that can block the add-to-basket decision — particularly for first-time buyers who need confidence before
        committing. This also harms SEO.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        This is likely a content/CMS issue rather than a code issue — the product data is incomplete. Ensure the
        product entry includes at minimum: fabric composition, key features (e.g. quick-dry, flatlock seams),
        fit type, and care instructions. Ticketable once the correct content is confirmed.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Conflicting free delivery thresholds"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="delivery-threshold-conflict"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Two different free delivery thresholds are visible simultaneously on the page. The site-wide trust bar in
        the header states "Free standard delivery on £55 spend." The product panel shows a promotional banner:
        "FREE DELIVERY ON ALL NEW-IN WHEN YOU SPEND £30 | AUTO APPLIES AT CHECKOUT." A user reading both cannot
        know which applies to this product or whether both are live concurrently.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Delivery cost uncertainty is a well-documented cause of checkout abandonment. Showing two different
        thresholds without clarification creates confusion and erodes trust in the pricing displayed. Users
        expecting £55 threshold may calculate incorrectly before checkout, leading to a surprise at the basket.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        If the £30 new-in delivery promotion is active site-wide during a campaign period, update the trust bar
        to reflect the current threshold. If it is product-specific, add clear qualifying copy ("on new-in items").
        The two messages should never show different thresholds without explicit context.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="FBT module pre-selects both add-ons, showing £62 total"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="fbt-preselected"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The "Frequently bought with" section pre-checks both recommended items by default — a Black colourway
        T-Shirt (£20) and Training Shorts (£22) — presenting a combined total of £62 alongside a primary
        "Add these to your routine" CTA. The user has not yet added the primary item to their basket.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-mp-training-tshirt-dark-grey-2026-06-04/fbt-desktop.png" alt="Frequently Bought With module showing two pre-selected add-ons and a £62 combined total" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Pre-selecting multiple items and surfacing a total 3× higher than the primary product price can create
        sticker shock, particularly for users who were assessing a £20 purchase. It can also read as a dark
        pattern, potentially causing users to abandon rather than de-select items. The "Add these to your routine"
        label uses Myprotein's nutrition stack language, which feels out-of-place for clothing.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Default to zero items pre-selected in the FBT module, or pre-select only one complementary item with
        clear opt-in affordance. Update the CTA copy to use clothing-appropriate language (e.g. "Complete the look"
        or "Add all to basket"). Consider showing the total only when items are selected.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Add to Basket button font size is 16px — spec says 14px"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="atb-font-size"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Computed style on the "Add to basket" button: <code>font-size: 16px; font-weight: 700</code>.
        The design token specification for button text is 14px Bold. Other design token values are correctly
        applied: Figtree font family ✓, 32px border-radius ✓, mint border ring (#94E5B5) ✓.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        A token deviation here means the button type doesn't match the design system specification, which can
        cause visual inconsistency if/when other button instances on the site render at 14px.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the Add to Basket button's font-size to <code>14px</code> to match the design token specification.
        Confirm the correct Tailwind class or CSS custom property is being applied.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Product title does not include selected colour name"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="title-no-colour"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The H1 reads "MP Men's Training Short Sleeve T-Shirt" — no colour is stated. The colour "Dark Grey"
        appears only in the breadcrumb trail, which is small and easy to miss. Without colour swatches visible
        in the panel (see <strong>colour-swatches-missing</strong>), there is no clear reinforcement of which
        variant the user is viewing.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users who arrive via direct links or search may not immediately register which colourway they're looking
        at, and may hesitate or add the wrong variant. On clothing PDPs, the selected colour should be clearly
        stated in or near the product title.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Append the current colour name to the H1 or display it as a sub-label directly below it:
        e.g. "MP Men's Training Short Sleeve T-Shirt" with "Colour: Dark Grey" below in smaller text.
        This is most impactful once colour swatches are restored.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="CTA label casing is inconsistent across the page"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="cta-casing"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The Add to Basket button in the FBT section renders as "Add to basket" (sentence case), while the
        sticky bottom bar renders "ADD TO BASKET" (all-caps). The same action is labelled differently
        depending on context.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Inconsistent labelling can create a minor sense of inconsistency or uncertainty. It also suggests a
        discrepancy between how the CTA is implemented in the two components — worth resolving to avoid
        future divergence.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Standardise on a single casing. The design system uses sentence case for primary CTAs ("Add to basket")
        — update the sticky bar to match.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      The Add to Basket button broadly adheres to design token values: Figtree font family is loaded and
      rendering correctly, the 32px border-radius is applied, and the mint outer ring
      (<code>border: 2px solid rgb(148, 229, 181)</code> = <code>#94E5B5</code>) is present — the brand
      signature CTA pattern is intact. The product title (H1) correctly uses 24px Medium Figtree as
      specified. The size selector chips render at 44px tall, meeting minimum touch-target requirements.
      The one clear deviation is the Add to Basket button's font-size at 16px rather than the specified
      14px Bold. The size chip border-radius computes to 0px on the button element itself, though visual
      inspection shows rounding — this appears to come from a wrapper container rather than the button,
      which is a structural inconsistency worth noting but does not create a visible issue currently.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      Size selector chips are 44×60px — meeting the WCAG 2.5.5 minimum target size of 44×44px.
      The Add to Basket button has sufficient contrast: white text on a dark teal background
      (<code>oklch(0.3162 0.055061 211.831)</code>, approximately #003942) exceeds the 4.5:1 AA
      requirement for normal text. The product image gallery appears to have zoom controls (visible
      magnifier icon) but it is not confirmed whether keyboard users can access the zoom interaction.
      The primary accessibility concern is the empty product panel: screen reader users will encounter
      a near-empty product form — no price, no colour, no rating — before reaching the size selector,
      which significantly degrades the experience for assistive technology users and may constitute a
      WCAG 1.3.1 (Info and Relationships) failure if the price is conveyed only via the sticky bar
      without appropriate ARIA association.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      The add-to-basket journey on this page is impaired primarily by what is missing rather than what
      is broken. A user arriving at this PDP cannot see the price, cannot see other colour options, and
      has no social proof — three of the most influential conversion signals on a clothing PDP — without
      those elements rendering in the panel. The sticky Add to Basket bar is well-implemented (correct
      design token signature, always visible) but it is doing too much heavy lifting by being the only
      place the price appears. The "Product Details" accordion offering only "Range: Clothing" also means
      users who want to verify fabric or fit before purchasing will leave disappointed. The FBT module,
      while a sensible upsell concept, risks alarming users with a £62 pre-selected total on what they
      expected to be a £20 product page. Taken together, these issues are likely to suppress add-to-basket
      rate measurably below the clothing PDP benchmark.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>
        <strong>Investigate and fix the panel rendering failures</strong> — restore price, colour swatches,
        and star rating to the product panel. These are likely a single root cause (data not reaching the
        panel template) and fixing them resolves three high-priority findings at once.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add proper product copy to the CMS entry</strong> — fabric composition, fit type, key
        features, and care instructions as a minimum. Coordinate between content and engineering on the
        correct fields to populate.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fix the FBT module default state</strong> — remove pre-selection of add-on items and
        update the CTA copy to use clothing-appropriate language.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Resolve the conflicting delivery threshold messaging</strong> — align the trust bar and
        product panel banner to show the same threshold, with campaign-specific messaging clearly scoped.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Correct the Add to Basket button font-size</strong> to 14px to match the design token spec,
        and standardise CTA label casing to sentence case across both button instances.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add colour label below the product title</strong> once colour swatches are restored, to
        clearly indicate the selected variant.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .findings-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .recommendations { padding-left: 20px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .recommendations li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }
</style>
